ted scholars take up the challenge to provide us with their conclusions about the early decisions that put the United States on the path to the greatest American tragedy since the Civil War. The tensions and turmoil that accompanied those decisions reveal the American presidency at the center of a storm of conflicting advice. The book is divided into four sections. Parts one and two delve into the political and military contexts of the early decisions. Part three raises the intriguing questions of Kennedy's and Johnson's roles in the conflict, particularly the thorny issue of whether Kennedy did, in fact, intend to withdraw from Vietnam and whether Johnson reversed that policy. Part four reveals an uncanny parallel between early Soviet policy toward Hanoi and U.S. policy toward Saigon.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975xUnited States. 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975zUnited States. 7aHISTORY / Military / Vietnam War.2bisacsh1 aBerman, Larry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDivine, Robert A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuiker, William J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaiduk, Ilya V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardner, Lloyd C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardner, Lloyd C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGibbons, William Conrad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGittinger, Ted, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHerring, George C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewman, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrados, John, econtributor.4ctb